Actually, the first program uses `sc.next()` which doesn't care about lines? It just reads tokens. But the input is given as 4 lines, each containing a string of 4 characters without spaces. So we can read 4 lines. However, to be safe, we read 4 tokens. But if the tokens are separated by newline, that's the same. We can do:

        char grid[4][5];  // 4 rows, each string of 4 characters plus null terminator. for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
            scanf("%s", grid[i]);
        }

  Then we have a flag `int found = 0;`

  Then:

        for (int u = 0; u < 3; u++) {   // because we are going to u+1, so u from 0 to 2 (inclusive)
            for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
                if ( (grid[u][i] == grid[u][i+1] && (grid[u+1][i] == grid[u][i] || grid[u+1][i+1] == grid[u][i]) ) || (grid[u+1][i] == grid[u+1][i+1] && (grid[u][i] == grid[u+1][i] || grid[u][i+1] == grid[u+1][i])) ) {
                    found = 1;
                    break;
                }
            }
            if (found) break;
        }

        if (found) {
            printf("YES\n");
        } else {
            printf("NO\n");
        } But wait: the condition in the second part of the OR uses `grid[u+1][i]` and `grid[u+1][i+1]` and then compares with `grid[u][i]` and `grid[u][i+1]`. However, note that the condition in the second part is:

        (str[u+1].charAt(i) == str[u+1].charAt(i+1) [so D: grid[u+1][i] == grid[u+1][i+1]]
        and then (E || F): 
            E: str[u].charAt(i) == str[u+1].charAt(i)   -> grid[u][i] == grid[u+1][i]
            F: str[u].charAt(i+1) == str[u+1].charAt(i)   -> grid[u][i+1] == grid[u+1][i]

  But note: the F condition in the original Java code was:

        str[u].charAt(i+1) == str[u+1].charAt(i)

  However, that is: the character at (u, i+1) is compared with (u+1, i). That seems asymmetric? But that is what the code says.
